                <MudExpansionPanel>
                    <TitleContent>
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.h4">WELCOME TO OUR TEAM!!</MudText>
                    </TitleContent>
                    <ChildContent>
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                            <p>
                                We welcome you to MIAS Fashion Manufacturing Company, Inc. We look forward to
                                the opportunity to work with you. We believe that employees are our most valuable
                                resource for our success. Our continued success in providing the highest quality products
                                to our customers depends on having quality people like yourself and your fellow
                                employees. We want you to enjoy your time here and are committed to helping you
                                succeed in your position at MIAS Fashion Manufacturing Company, Inc.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                We have prepared this Employee Handbook as a guide to answer some of the questions
                                that you may have concerning MIAS Fashion Manufacturing Company, Inc. and its
                                policies. This Employee Handbook is intended solely as guide. Please read it thoroughly
                                and if you have questions about the contents of this Employee Handbook, please contact
                                your General Manager for assistance.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                We hope that you find your time with us to be an enjoyable and rewarding experience.
                                Once again, welcome to MIAS Fashion Manufacturing Company, Inc.
                            </p>
                            Sincerely,<br />
                            Peter Ahn<br />
                            President and CEO<br />
                        </MudText>
                    </ChildContent>
                </MudExpansionPanel>

                @*********Employment Policies Section*********@
                <MudExpansionPanel>
                    <TitleContent>
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.h5">EMPLOYMENT POLICIES</MudText>
                    </TitleContent>
                    <ChildContent>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">AT-WILL EMPLOYMENT</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Other than certain employees who have entered into separate employment agreements, all
                                        employment at Company is <strong>“AT-WILL.”</strong>This means that both employees and Company
                                        have the right to terminate employment at any time, with or without advance notice, and
                                        with or without cause. Employees also may be demoted or disciplined, and the terms of
                                        their employment may be altered at any time, with or without cause, at the discretion of
                                        Company. No one other than the President has the authority to alter this arrangement, to
                                        enter into an agreement for employment for a specified period of time, or to make any
                                        agreement contrary to this policy, and any such agreement must be in writing and must be
                                        signed by the President and by the affected employee.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">IMMIGRATION LAW COMPLIANCE (I-9)</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Federal and state law requires all employers to verify each new employee’s identity and
                                        legal ability to work in the United States. In compliance with the federal Immigration
                                        Reform and Control Act of 1986 (IRCA), as amended, Company is committed to
                                        employing only individuals who are authorized to work in the United States. All
                                        employees, upon being hired, must complete an IRS Form I-9 to provide proof of identity
                                        and eligibility to legally work in the U.S. Employees must present original documents.
                                        Providing false identification or making false statements on the I-9 form shall be grounds
                                        for immediate discharge. Before commencing work, newly rehired employees must also
                                        complete the form if they have not previously filed an I-9 with Company if their previous
                                        I-9 is more than three years old, or if their previous I-9 is no longer valid.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Current employees are also required to update work eligibility status, should their status
                                        expire or change. Furthermore, Company will not be responsible for updating an
                                        employee’s legal status and may not under any circumstances
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">EQUAL EMPLOYMENT OPPORTUNITY STATEMENT</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Company provides equal employment opportunities (EEO) to all employees and
                                        applicants for employment without regard to race, color, religion, gender, sexual
                                        orientation, gender identity, national origin, age, disability, genetic information, marital
                                        status, amnesty or status as a covered veteran in accordance with applicable federal, state
                                        and local laws. Company complies with applicable state and local laws governing
                                        nondiscrimination in employment in every location in which Company has facilities.
                                        This policy applies to all terms and conditions of employment, including hiring,
                                        placement, promotion, termination, layoff, recall, transfer, leaves of absence,
                                        compensation and training.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Company is strongly committed to and is actively committed to equal employment
                                        opportunity in the workplace. As such, Company offers employment opportunities on a
                                        non-discriminatory basis to all qualified individuals, including those who may happen to be disabled.
                                        Company will offer reasonable accommodation to disabled individuals,
                                        where appropriate, to permit them to perform the essential functions of their job.
                                        Company expressly prohibits any form of unlawful employee harassment based on race,
                                        color, religion, gender, sexual orientation, national origin, age, genetic information,
                                        disability or veteran status. Improper interference with the ability of Company’s
                                        employees to perform their expected job duties is absolutely not tolerated. All employees,
                                        as per the law, must be at least 18 years of age. Employees under the age of 18 must
                                        comply with all federal wage and hour guidelines, no exceptions. The required work
                                        permits must be supplied when applicable.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">AMERICANS WITH DISABILITIES ACT</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        The Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) and the Americans with Disabilities
                                        Amendments Act, known as the ADAAA, are federal laws that prohibit employers with
                                        15 or more employees from discriminating against applicants and individuals with
                                        disabilities and that when needed provide reasonable accommodations to applicants and
                                        employees who are qualified for a job, with or without reasonable accommodations, so
                                        that they may perform the essential job duties of the position.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        It is the policy of Company to comply with all federal and state laws concerning the
                                        employment of persons with disabilities and to act in accordance with regulations and
                                        guidance issued by the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC).
                                        Furthermore, it is our policy not to discriminate against qualified individuals with
                                        disabilities in regard to application procedures, hiring, advancement, discharge,
                                        compensation, training or other terms, conditions and privileges of employment.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Company will reasonably accommodate qualified individuals with a disability so that
                                        they can perform the essential functions of a job unless doing so causes a direct threat to
                                        these individuals or others in the workplace and the threat cannot be eliminated by
                                        reasonable accommodation and/or if the accommodation creates an undue hardship to
                                        Company. If you have a disability that requires some accommodation in the workplace,
                                        please talk with the General Manager so that a full understanding of the disability and an
                                        evaluation of the appropriate accommodation, if any, can be made. We will treat
                                        information concerning disabilities in a confidential manner consistent with the need to
                                        protect the safety and health of the other employees and the public.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">EMPLOYEE BACKGROUND CHECK</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        In compliance with the Los Angeles Fair Chance Initiative for Hiring, Company will not
                                        inquire about or require an applicant to disclose their criminal history. Upon making a
                                        conditional offer of employment, Company may conduct a job-related background check
                                        or may request a comprehensive background check according to the position applied for
                                        A comprehensive background check may consist of prior criminal record, employment
                                        verification, professional reference checks, and education confirmation.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">PRE-EMPLOYMENT SCREENING ASSESSMENTS</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        All applicants are required to successfully complete several job-related
                                        screenings/assessments. To maintain a safe work environment Company requires the
                                        successful completion of various types of screenings/assessments as a condition of
                                        employment. All federal, state, and local requirements concerning job related screenings
                                        of Company’s employees are adhered to. All applicants being considered for
                                        employment with Company may be required to submit to a pre-employment physical and
                                        drug screening.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">MEDICAL EXAMINATION/ILLEGAL DRUG AND ALCOHOL TESTS</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Company establishes its right to require an employee to submit to a medical examination
                                        and/or tests for illegal drugs or alcohol when Company has a business need for such
                                        medical exam/tests or has reasonable suspicion that an employee is under the influence.
                                        Failure to submit to a medical exam/test, or a test giving positive results, is grounds for
                                        immediate termination.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">PERSONNEL RECORDS AND ADMINISTRATION</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item;">
                                    <p>
                                        <b><u>Confidentiality:</u></b> It is necessary for Company to maintain certain records about
                                        you which are directly related to your job and Company’s responsibilities. At all
                                        times Company will do its best to balance your rights to privacy with the
                                        Company's need to collect and use your personal information.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item;">
                                    <p>
                                        <b><u>Reviewing Your Personnel File:</u></b> Your personnel file is confidential and is
                                        available to you, your manager and upper management personnel. It will only
                                        contain such information as is needed by Company to conduct its business or as is
                                        required by Federal or State law. You have the right to review your personnel
                                        file. Ask your manager to make appropriate arrangements and an appointment
                                        will be made for a mutually convenient time. No copies of documents in your file
                                        may be made, with the exception of documents that you have previously signed.
                                        You may add your version of any disputed item to the file.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item;">
                                    <p>
                                        All medical records and background check reports, if any, will be kept in a
                                        separate confidential file.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">CHANGE OF PERSONAL DATA</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Employees have the responsibility to ensure that their personal files are up to date.
                                        Company should be notified of any change in:
                                    </p>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Legal Name
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Home Address
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Home contact telephone number
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Contact person in case of an emergency
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Tax Filing Status (W-4)
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <p>Any other records Compnay deems necessary</p>
                                    </MudText>
                                    <p>
                                        Any change needs to be reported in writing without delay to the management. Failure to
                                        keep your records up to date shall relieve Company of any of its responsibilities as a
                                        result of inaccurate information. Falsification of any information can result in legal
                                        difficulties with both State and Federal agencies and/or dismissal from Company.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">HEALTH RELATED ISSUES</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        An employee who becomes aware of any health-related issue that may impact the
                                        employee’s job performance should notify their manager of his/her health-related issue as
                                        soon as possible.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">EMPLOYEE CLASSIFICATION</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        In order to determine an employee’s status and eligibility for various benefits, the
                                        following employment classifications have been established.
                                    </p>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <b><u>Regular Employees</u></b>
                                        <p>
                                            Regular employees are those who are hired to work on a regular schedule. Regular
                                            employees may be classified as full-time or part-time.
                                        </p>
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <b><u>Full-Time Employees</u></b>
                                        <p>
                                            Full-time employees are defined as those employees who are hired to work on a regular
                                            basis a shift of 40 hours or more a week.
                                        </p>
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <b><u>Part-Time Employees</u></b>
                                        <p>
                                            Part-time employees are defined as (i) those non-exempt employees who are hired to
                                            work on a regular basis a shift of less than forty (40) hours but not less than twenty (20)
                                            hours a week and are paid on an hourly basis and (ii) those exempt employees who have
                                            an expectation and agreement with Company that they will work on a regular basis less
                                            than forty (40) hours a week (or the monthly or yearly equivalent).
                                        </p>
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <b><u>Temporary Employees</u></b>
                                        <p>
                                            Temporary employees are those who are hired for a short-term, seasonal or specific
                                            period of time or for a specified work project. A temporary employee is hired with the
                                            understanding that employment will cease at the expiration of a specific period of time or
                                            when services are no longer needed. Temporary employees are not eligible for employee
                                            benefits except where mandated by applicable law.
                                        </p>
                                    </MudText>
                                    <p>
                                        Temporary changes in the number of hours do not affect an employee’s status, and the
                                        preceding definitions are not to be construed as a guarantee of work hours.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        In addition, employees may be either exempt (not subject to overtime and certain other
                                        regulations of working hours) or non-exempt (subject to overtime and related regulations).
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>

                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">NON-EXEMPT AND EXEMPT</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        All jobs are defined as "exempt" or "non-exempt" using the criteria established by the
                                        Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA), a federal law defining the requirements for paying
                                        overtime, and California law (or other state law, as applicable).
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                    <b><u>Non-Exempt:</u></b> Employees performing non-exempt jobs are not exempted from the
                                    minimum wage or overtime provisions of the FLSA and applicable state laws. A
                                    non-exempt employee is often an hourly wage employee but can be a salaried
                                    employee (whose regular time hourly rate would be 1/40th of the weekly salary).
                                    A non-exempt employee is entitled to overtime pay for work in excess of 40 hours
                                    in a workweek or, in California (or under any other applicable state law) 8 hours
                                    per workday.
                                </MudText>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                    <b><u>Exempt:</u></b> Employees performing exempt jobs are exempted from the minimum
                                    wage, overtime and certain other provisions of the FLSA and California law (or
                                    other state law, as applicable). An exempt employee is paid on a salary basis to
                                    accomplish responsibilities and tasks, without regard to the time required.
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">PROBATIONARY PERIOD</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        All employees are considered to be in an initial evaluation period for the first ninety (90)
                                        calendar days from date of hire. During this period, both employee and Company have
                                        the opportunity to determine whether they desire to continue the employment relationship.
                                        Company can extend the probationary period for an additional 30 to 90 days, in its sole
                                        and absolute discretion, if it determines that such an extension is appropriate. Company
                                        or the employee can terminate the employment relationship at any time during the
                                        probationary period for any reason, with or without cause and with or without notice.
                                        Employees will not be eligible for any benefits during the probationary period.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        The successful completion of the probationary period is only one step in your
                                        employment at Company and does not mean that Company will thereafter employ you
                                        for any specific period of time.
                                        <i>
                                            Satisfactory completion of the probationary period does
                                            not alter the AT-WILL character of the employment relationship at Company.
                                        </i>
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">TRAINING</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        To help you be successful in your job you will receive adequate training. You will not be
                                        expected to be on your own until you are ready. We spend considerable time and money
                                        educating our trainers to prepare each new employee for their job. We want you to be a
                                        knowledgeable and productive member of our staff.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">EVALUATIONS</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        All employees receive online performance evaluations. The evaluation process is
                                        intended to let you know how well you’re performing and to help you to be more
                                        effective and productive. The evaluation also gives you the opportunity to share your
                                        thoughts about your performance and future goals with your manager.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        The evaluation process is an opportunity to identify accomplishments and strengths as
                                        well as to openly discuss areas and goals for any improvement. At the sole discretion of
                                        Company, depending on your position and performance, you may be eligible for a pay
                                        increase. Pay increases are not guaranteed. Rewards are based solely on a person’s job
                                        performance and results.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">SCHEDULE</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Schedules are prepared to meet the work demands of Company. As work demands
                                        change, management reserves the right to adjust working hours and shifts. Each
                                        employee is responsible for working their shifts.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        You should arrive for your shift and clock in when your shift begins and be ready to start
                                        work immediately.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Schedule changes may be allowed only if you get a manager’s approval. To be valid, the
                                        manager must indicate and initial the change on the posted schedule. We do, however,
                                        ask that you remember how crucial each position is to the proper functioning of
                                        Company. Please remember that even though we will try to comply with your requests,
                                        there is no assurance that you will be approved for the requested schedule change.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                    </ChildContent>
                </MudExpansionPanel>

                @*********Payment Procedures Section*********@
                <MudExpansionPanel>
                    <TitleContent>
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.h5">PAYMENT PROCEDURES</MudText>
                    </TitleContent>
                    <ChildContent>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">TIME REPORTING</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Non-exempt employees are required to use Company’s time keeping system to accurately
                                        measure the daily work hours, including lunch periods if taken. Currently, Company’s
                                        time keeping system is to record all daily work hours and to submit to Human Resources
                                        pursuant to Company’s payroll schedule. Both salaried employees (non-exempt only)
                                        and hourly employees (non-exempt) are required to use Company’s time keeping system
                                        for the accurate time keeping of the employee’s hours worked.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Tampering, altering, or falsifying time records or recording time on another employee’s
                                        time sheet is not allowed and may result in disciplinary action, up to and including
                                        termination.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">WORKWEEK</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        For pay purposes, our official workweek is seven (7) consecutive days, beginning at
                                        12:01 a.m. on Monday and ending at midnight the following Sunday.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">PAYROLL CHECKS</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Employees are usually paid on bi-weekly basis. If the pay-day falls on a Saturday or
                                        Sunday, you will be paid on the Friday prior to payday. If the payday falls on a Company
                                        recognized holiday, you will receive your pay on the last workday prior to the holiday.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">PAYROLL DEDUCTIONS</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Your paycheck will indicate your gross earnings as well as deductions for federal and
                                        state withholding taxes and social security and Medicare taxes. Federal and state
                                        withholding taxes are authorized by you based on the information you furnished to us on
                                        form W-4.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        As per state law, Company complies with court orders in connection to garnishments
                                        from employee paychecks as directed by the proper authorities. You will be notified of
                                        any court-ordered payroll deductions.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">CHANGE OF ADDRESS, PHONE, E-MAIL, W-4</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        We ask that you report any address changes to Payroll Manager as soon as possible so
                                        that your year-end statement of income and deductions, form W-2, will be mailed to the
                                        correct address or sent to the correct email.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">OVERTIME</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Occasionally it may be necessary for an employee to work beyond his or her normal
                                        workday hours. Overtime pay is paid only when work is scheduled, approved, and made
                                        known to you in advance by your supervisor. Under no circumstances shall an employee
                                        work overtime without the prior approval of his or her supervisor.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Overtime pay will be paid as required by state and federal regulations. All non-exempt
                                        employees who work more than eight (8) hours up to twelve (12) hours per workday,
                                        more than forty (40) hours per workweek, and first (8) hours of work during the seventh
                                        (7th) consecutive day of work in a workweek will be entitled to receive overtime pay at
                                        the rate of 1.5 times the straight time.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Overtime pay at the rate of two (2) times your regular hourly rate of pay is paid for all
                                        hours of work performed in excess of twelve (12) hours in one work day and for all hours
                                        of work in excess of eight (8) hours on the seventh consecutive day of work in any work
                                        week.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Exempt employees may have to work hours beyond their normal schedules as work
                                        demands require. <b>No overtime compensation will be paid to exempt employees.</b>
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        <b>
                                            All overtime must be approved in advance by your supervisor or manager by
                                            submitting a written overtime request form. If you work unauthorized overtime,
                                            you are subject to disciplinary action.
                                        </b>
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">OVERTIME PRE-APPROVAL</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Non-exempt employees must receive overtime pre-approval using the Company’s form.
                                        Reporting overtime worked does NOT eliminate the requirement to obtain advance
                                        consent from your manager. A non-exempt employee who reports unauthorized overtime
                                        worked will be paid the appropriate rate for such reported overtime work, but shall be
                                        subject to discipline, including termination, for working unauthorized overtime hours.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">CALL BACK PAY</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Company recognizes your right to privacy during your non-working hours. However,
                                        situations do occur that may require your services at other than your regularly scheduled
                                        work shift. If such a situation does arise and you are a non-exempt employee who is
                                        called into work at a time other than your regularly scheduled shift or are called back to
                                        work within the same calendar day after completing a regular work shift, you will be paid
                                        for the greater of two (2) hours or the actual number of hours worked.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">REPORTING PAY</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        If you report for work as scheduled but are not put to work or are furnished less than onehalf
                                        (1/2) the scheduled day’s work, you will be paid for one-half (1/2) of the scheduled
                                        day’s work. Payment will be for a minimum of two (2) hours up to a maximum of four
                                        (4) hours at your regular, hourly rate. However, reporting pay will not be paid if:
                                    </p>
                                    <ol>
                                        <li>
                                            Operations cannot commence or continue due to threats to employees or property,
                                            or when recommended by civil authorities
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            Public utilities fail to supply electricity, water or gas, or there is a failure in the
                                            public utilities or sewer system
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            The interruption of work is caused by conditions beyond Company is control.
                                            Hours paid but not worked under this provision will not be used in the calculation
                                            of overtime pay
                                        </li>
                                    </ol>
                                </MudText>

                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">BUSINESS EXPENSES</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Employees may occasionally incur expenses on behalf of Company. Company will
                                        reimburse employees for typical business expenses, such as mileage (for example, when
                                        Company asks an employee to travel to a different jobsite during the workday) and
                                        certain job-related supplies or materials.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Normal job-related expenses will be reimbursed if the expenditure has been pre-approved in
                                        writing and signed by the department manager. Reimbursable expenses are to be itemized
                                        on the Company’s expense report and submitted to the department manager for review
                                        and approval along with original receipts as instructed by the Accounting Team. Expense
                                        reports and receipts must be submitted to accounts payable in order to be processed.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">DISCRETIONARY BONUS</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Company practices a Discretionary Bonus policy with its employees. Discretionary
                                        Bonuses are provided to eligible employees. Eligibility is determined by Company and
                                        amounts of bonuses shall be in keeping with Company policy.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Note, Company’s policy regarding equal employment opportunities (i.e., based on jobrelated
                                        nondiscriminatory criteria only, not on any employee’s race, color, religion, sex,
                                        national origin, age, disability, sexual orientation, marital status, etc.), is and will be
                                        consistent in determining bonuses for its employees. Further, any paid bonuses shall be
                                        consistent with local, state and federal laws (i.e., tax reporting and classification of
                                        bonuses).
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        No bonus will be provided to terminated employees and it will be paid on pro-rata basis
                                        for employees who are on a leave of absence.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                    </ChildContent>
                </MudExpansionPanel>

                @*********Meal & Rest Break Periods Policy Section*********@
                <MudExpansionPanel>
                    <TitleContent>
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.h5">MEAL & REST BREAK PERIODS POLICY</MudText>
                    </TitleContent>
                    <ChildContent>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">MEAL BREAK PERIOD POLICY</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        An unpaid meal break period is normally scheduled near the midpoint of the work period.
                                        Each hourly employee is required by Company to take an unpaid meal period of one hour
                                        (1) duration for any workday longer than five (5) hours, with the meal period to
                                        commence (and the employee to punch out) no later than five (5) hours after the
                                        commencement of the employee’s work shift. Employees must punch out the timecard
                                        before and after the meal break.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Employees whose daily work schedule will be completed in six hours or less may, upon
                                        agreement with Company, waive the daily meal period. Each employee who works more
                                        than ten hours in one day is required by Company to take, during that workday, a second
                                        unpaid meal period of not less than one (1) hour, except that an employee whose work
                                        during that workday will be completed in 12 hours or less, and who took a first meal
                                        period commencing at or prior to working five (5) hours during that workday, may waive
                                        the second meal period.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Employees are relieved and released of all duties during the meal period. If any manager
                                        or Company representative encourages Employee to work during their meal period
                                        without pay, Employee is to report such conduct immediately to Management. Any
                                        employee who takes less than the required meal break(s) or fails to punch out and punch
                                        in for the required meal periods, or does both, repeatedly during any pay period, will be
                                        subject to discipline, up to and including termination.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">REST BREAK PERIODS POLICY</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        A paid rest break period, consisting of a minimum of ten (10) minutes, is normally
                                        scheduled near the midpoint of each half of a full workday. Non-exempt employees are
                                        required by law and Company policy to take a paid rest break, consisting of a minimum
                                        of ten (10) minutes, during every four (4) hours worked or major fraction thereof. If, for
                                        example, employee works 6.5 hours, Employee is entitled to 20 minutes of break time, 10
                                        minutes for the initial 4 hours worked and another 10 minutes for the major fraction of
                                        the remaining 4 hours, i.e., 2.5 hours. Further, if you are scheduled to work two (2) or
                                        more hours overtime in one workday, you are required by law and Company policy to
                                        take an additional paid rest break, consisting of a minimum of ten (10) minutes, at the end
                                        of the first eight (8) hours of the workday.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Violations of this Break Period policy will be subject to discipline, up to and including
                                        termination.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">LACTATION ACCOMMODATION (LABOR CODE SECTION 1030)</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        In compliance with Labor Code Section 1030, Company will provide a reasonable
                                        amount of break time to accommodate an employee desiring to express breast milk for
                                        the employee’s infant child. The break time shall, if possible, be taken concurrently with
                                        other break periods already provided. Non-exempt employees should clock out for any
                                        time taken that does not run concurrently with normally scheduled rest periods, and such
                                        time will be unpaid unless otherwise required by federal or state law. Company will also
                                        make a reasonable effort to provide the employee with the use of a room or other location
                                        in close proximity to the employee’s work area, for the employee to express milk in
                                        private.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Employees should notify their supervisor or the Human Resources to request time and
                                        make other necessary arrangements to express breast milk under this policy.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        No provision of this policy applies or is enforced if it conflicts with or is superseded by
                                        any requirement or prohibition contained in a state or local law or regulation. Anyone
                                        with knowledge of such a conflict or potential conflict should contact the Human
                                        Resources.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                    </ChildContent>
                </MudExpansionPanel>

                @*********Code of Conduct Section*********@
                <MudExpansionPanel>
                    <TitleContent>
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.h5">CODE OF CONDUCT</MudText>
                    </TitleContent>
                    <ChildContent>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">INTRODUCTION</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Company expects each employee to conduct himself/herself in a professional and ethical
                                        manner. This means that, among other things, employees are expected to conduct
                                        themselves in a manner that will uphold the Company’s reputation for excellent customer
                                        service, courteousness, efficiency, safety and timeliness.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        While Company reserves the right to dismiss employees at any time, it also may take
                                        other disciplinary measures against employees who violate work rules or fail to
                                        satisfactorily perform their job duties. Examples of disciplinary action include a warning
                                        letter, suspension without pay, demotion, or discharge.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        In an effort to alert employees to expectations of them and to apprise them of their
                                        obligations and responsibilities regarding their conduct, listed below are examples of
                                        types of behavior that may result in disciplinary action. The first list is a list of offenses
                                        that typically will be more serious and even result in immediate dismissal. The second list
                                        is a list of offenses that are not as grave but are still likely to result in disciplinary action.
                                        Of course, Company reserves the right to determine appropriate disciplinary action based
                                        on the individual circumstances in its sole discretion. Because we cannot anticipate every
                                        situation that might arise, these lists merely provide examples of problematic conduct.
                                        Company expects employees to always behave lawfully, ethically, and with good sense.
                                    </p>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <u><b>Actions Which May Result in Immediate Discharge</b></u>
                                        <ol>
                                            <li>
                                                Dishonest conduct, including, but not limited to, unauthorized taking or
                                                possession of Company’s property, unauthorized possession or taking of a fellow
                                                employee’s property, taking bribes, or unauthorized charges against Company’s
                                                account.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Any unauthorized possession, use, purchase, sale, transfer, or being under the
                                                influence of an illegal drug, alcohol, or cannabis products on Company premises.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Working for a competitor or engaging in any activity that poses a conflict with the
                                                Company's interests or appears to do so.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Taking money, merchandises or services from a customer or vendor for personal
                                                gain without authorization.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Improperly disclosing or using trade secrets, proprietary, or confidential
                                                information about Company, its partners, its employees, or its agents.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Insubordination, derogatory or defamatory behavior toward management
                                                personnel, other employees, Company, or its partners.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>Sexual or other harassment.</li>
                                            <li>
                                                False statements, misrepresentations, or omissions on documents or records, such
                                                as resumes, job applications, or timecards.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>Failing to return to work after an authorized leave of absence.</li>
                                            <li>
                                                Possession of firearms or other weapons on Company premises or while
                                                performing Company business without authorization.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>Violent conduct or threat of violence.</li>
                                            <li>Felony conviction or pleading of no contest.</li>
                                            <li>Gambling on Company premises.</li>
                                            <li>Serious misconduct of any kind.</li>
                                        </ol>
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <b><u>Other Actions Which May Result in Warnings/Suspension</u></b>
                                        <ol>
                                            <li>
                                                Engaging in outside activities that affect your availability, efficiency, or ability to
                                                perform your job or that negatively affect Company or its professional reputation.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Failure to report to work without proper notification to your manager and/or a
                                                justifiable reason for such failure.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>Engaging in horseplay on the job.</li>
                                            <li>
                                                Using Company time, property, or facilities for purposes not directly related to
                                                Company business.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Using Company telephone lines or other communications systems for excessive
                                                personal use or other unauthorized purposes.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Engaging in rude or improper behavior or failing to be courteous to members of
                                                the public and other employees at work.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Inability to perform, or to perform in a substandard manner, the essential
                                                functions of your job or an assigned duty or responsibility.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Repeated tardiness and/or absences, except for authorized leaves of absence,
                                                regardless of whether some or most of the absences were excused.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                The sale, solicitation of financial contributions or distribution of materials in work
                                                areas or during working times.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>Violating Company rule(s) and/or regulation(s).</li>
                                            <li>Failure to observe safety rules and regulations.</li>
                                            <li>
                                                Damaging Company property or the property of others, either intentionally or
                                                through gross negligence.
                                            </li>
                                        </ol>
                                        <p>
                                            Nothing herein alters the at-will nature of the employee’s employment
                                            with Company.
                                        </p>
                                    </MudText>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">HARASSMENT</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        It is Company’s policy to treat all personnel with dignity and respect and make personnel
                                        decisions without regard to race, sex, age, color, national origin, religion, or disability.
                                        We strive to provide everyone a workplace that is free of harassment of any kind.
                                        Employees are encouraged to promptly report incidences of harassment.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Company is committed to providing a workplace in which all individuals are treated with
                                        respect and dignity and will endeavor to maintain a work environment that nourishes
                                        respect for the dignity of each individual. Company expects that all relationships among
                                        persons in the workplace will be business-like and free of bias, prejudice, and
                                        harassment. Company specifically prohibits harassment of any kind, whether verbal,
                                        physical or visual, that is based on an individual's race, color, religion, national origin,
                                        ancestry, age, physical or mental disability, marital status, medical condition, sex,
                                        pregnancy, childbirth, or related medical condition, sexual orientation, veteran status or
                                        any other category protected by state or federal law.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        This policy applies to all applicants and staff, and, pursuant to the policy, Company will
                                        not tolerate harassment, discrimination, or retaliation, whether engaged in by supervisors,
                                        managers, co-workers, contractors, vendors, or customers. Similarly, Company will not
                                        tolerate unlawful harassment by its employees of non-employees with whom Company’s
                                        employees have a business, service, or professional relationship.
                                    </p>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <b><u>Prohibited Conduct</u></b>
                                        <p>
                                            Prohibited conduct includes unwelcome verbal, physical, and/or visual conduct that
                                            creates an intimidating, offensive, or hostile working environment or that interferes with
                                            work performance. Harassing conduct can take many forms and includes, but is not
                                            limited to, slurs, jokes, statements, gestures, pictures, or cartoons regarding an employee's
                                            sex, race, color, national origin, religion, age, physical or mental disability, ancestry,
                                            marital status, or any other category protected by applicable federal or state law.
                                            Sexually harassing conduct in particular may include all of these prohibited actions, as
                                            well as other unwelcome conduct, such as requests for sexual favors, conversation
                                            containing sexual comments, and unwelcome sexual advances. Sexual harassment can be
                                            by a person of either the same or the other sex.
                                        </p>
                                        <p>
                                            Conduct constitutes unlawful harassment when (1) submission to the conduct is made
                                            either an explicit or implicit condition of employment; (2) submission to or rejection of
                                            the conduct is used as the basis for an employment decision; or (3) the harassment
                                        </p>
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <b><u>Sexual Harassment</u></b>
                                        <p>
                                            All of our employees have a right to be free from sexual harassment. Company does not
                                            condone actions, words, jokes, or comments that a reasonable person would regard as
                                            sexually harassing or coercive.
                                        </p>
                                        <p>
                                            Sexual harassment encompasses any sexual attention, from either gender, which is
                                            unwanted and is defined as unwelcome advances, requests for sexual favors, or other
                                            verbal or physical conduct of a sexual nature when:
                                        </p>
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Submission is made an express or implied term or condition of employment or
                                        status in a class, program, or activity.
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Submission to or rejection of the behavior is used to make an employment
                                        decision (such as hiring or promotion).
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        The conduct has the purpose or effect of unreasonably interfering with a person’s
                                        work performance or creates an intimidating, hostile or offensive environment for
                                        work, including harassment in the workplace from an outside party, such as a
                                        vendor.
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Sexual harassment may take many forms, for example:
                                        <ol>
                                            <li>Physical assault</li>
                                            <li>
                                                Direct or implied threats that submission to sexual advances will be a
                                                condition of employment, work schedule, promotion, job assignments,
                                                evaluation, wages, or any other condition of employment.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>Direct propositions of a sexual nature.</li>
                                            <li>Comments of a sexual nature.</li>
                                            <li>Sexually explicit statements, questions, jokes or anecdotes.</li>
                                            <li>
                                                Unnecessary touching, patting, hugging, or brushing against a person’s
                                                body.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Remarks of a sexual nature about a person’s clothing, body, sexual
                                                activity, or previous sexual experience.
                                            </li>
                                        </ol>
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Employees need to be concerned not only with the intent of their actions of this
                                        kind but also the effects; while sexual harassment involves repeated, unwanted
                                        sexual attention, persons involved in isolated or inadvertent incidents demonstrate
                                        insensitivity toward others. Repeated occurrences will be considered intentional
                                        violations of the policy.
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Anyone who feels it is necessary to discuss what may appear to be sexual
                                        harassment should <b><u>report the harassment promptly to at least two people</u></b> who
                                        are a manager or in management capacity. Your report will be kept as confidential
                                        as possible. A prompt and thorough investigation will be made. If a claim is
                                        substantiated, Company will take immediate and appropriate action, including
                                        discipline and possible termination.
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <b><u>Sexual Harassment Training</u></b>
                                    </MudText>
                                    <p>
                                        Company provides at least two hours of sexual harassment training to all supervisory
                                        employees and at least one hour of sexual harassment training to all nonsupervisory
                                        employees within six months of hire or promotion.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Company provides sexual harassment training and education to each employee once
                                        every two years and to seasonal and temporary employees or any employee who is hired
                                        to work for less than six months within 30 calendar days after the hire date or within 100
                                        hours worked, whichever occurs first.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                    <p><u>Complaint Process</u></p>
                                    Individuals who believe that they have been the victim of conduct prohibited by this
                                    policy statement or who believe that they have witnessed such conduct should discuss
                                    their concerns with their immediate supervisor, Human Resources or any member of
                                    management or contact Complaint Hotline at (562) 906-1060 x 107.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        When possible, Company encourages individuals who believe that they are being
                                        subjected to such conduct to promptly advise the offender that his or her behavior is
                                        unwelcome and request that it be discontinued. Often this action alone will resolve the
                                        problem. Company recognizes, however, that an individual may prefer to pursue the
                                        matter through complaint procedures. Company encourages the prompt reporting of
                                        complaints or concerns so that rapid and constructive action can be taken before
                                        relationships become irreparably strained. Therefore, although no fixed reporting period
                                        has been established, early reporting and intervention have proven to be the most
                                        effective method of resolving actual or perceived incidents of harassment.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Any reported allegations of harassment, discrimination or retaliation will be investigated
                                        promptly. The investigation may include individual interviews with the parties involved
                                        and, where necessary, with individuals who may have observed the alleged conduct or
                                        may have other relevant knowledge.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Confidentiality will be maintained throughout the investigatory process to the extent
                                        consistent with adequate investigation and appropriate corrective action.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Retaliation against an individual for reporting harassment or discrimination or for
                                        participating in an investigation of a claim of harassment or discrimination is a serious
                                        violation of this policy and, like harassment or discrimination itself, will be subject to
                                        disciplinary action. Acts of retaliation should be reported immediately and will be
                                        promptly investigated and addressed. Misconduct constituting harassment, discrimination
                                        or retaliation will be dealt with appropriately.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">WORKPLACE BULLYING</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Company defines bullying as “repeated inappropriate behavior, either direct or indirect,
                                        whether verbal, physical or otherwise, conducted by one or more persons against another
                                        or others, at the place of work and/or in the course of employment.” Such behavior
                                        violates Company policy that all employees will be treated with dignity and respect.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        The purpose of this policy is to communicate to all employees, including supervisors,
                                        manager and president, that Company will not tolerate bullying behavior. Employees
                                        found in violation of this policy will be disciplined up to and including termination.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Bullying may be intentional or unintentional. However, it must be noted that where an
                                        allegation of bullying is made, the intention of the alleged bully is irrelevant and will not
                                        be given consideration when considering disciplinary action. As in sexual harassment, it
                                        is the effect of the behavior upon the individual that is important. Company considers the
                                        following types of behavior as examples of bullying:
                                    </p>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Verbal bullying: Slandering, ridiculing, or maligning a person or his/her family;
                                        persistent name calling that is hurtful, insulting or humiliating; using a person as
                                        the butt of jokes; abusive and offensive remarks.
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Physical bullying: Pushing, shoving, kicking, poking, tripping, assault, or threat of
                                        physical assault; damage to a person’s work area or property.
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Gesture bullying: Nonverbal threatening gestures or glances that convey
                                        threatening messages.
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Exclusion: Socially or physically excluding or disregarding a person in workrelated
                                        activities.
                                    </MudText>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">VIOLENCE IN THE WORKPLACE</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        All employees, customers, vendors, and business associates must be treated with courtesy
                                        and respect at all times. Employees are expected to refrain from conduct that may be
                                        dangerous to others.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Conduct that threatens intimidates or coerces another employee, customer, vendor, or
                                        business associate will not be tolerated. Company resources may not be used to threaten,
                                        stalk or harass anyone at the workplace or outside the workplace. Company treats threats
                                        coming from an abusive personal relationship as it does other forms of violence.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Indirect or direct threats of violence, incidents of actual violence and suspicious
                                        individuals or activities should be reported as soon as possible to a supervisor, security
                                        personnel, Human Resources, or any member of senior management. When reporting a
                                        threat or incident of violence, the employee should be as specific and detailed as possible.
                                        Employees should not place themselves in peril, nor should they attempt to intercede
                                        during an incident. Employees should promptly inform the Human Resources of any
                                        protective or restraining order that they have obtained that lists the workplace as a
                                        protected area. Employees are encouraged to report safety concerns with regard to
                                        intimate partner violence. Company will not retaliate against employees making goodfaith
                                        reports.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Company will promptly and thoroughly investigate all reports of threats of violence or
                                        incidents of actual violence and of suspicious individuals or activities. The identity of the
                                        individual making a report will be protected as much as possible. Company will not
                                        retaliate against employees making good-faith reports of violence, threats or suspicious
                                        individuals or activities. In order to maintain workplace safety and the integrity of its
                                        investigation, Company may suspend employees suspected of workplace violence or
                                        threats of violence, either with or without pay, pending investigation.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Anyone found to be responsible for threats of or actual violence or other conduct that is
                                        in violation of these guidelines will be subject to prompt disciplinary action up to and
                                        including termination of employment.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Company encourages employees to bring their disputes to the attention of their
                                        supervisors or Human Resources before the situation escalates. Company will not
                                        discipline employees for raising such concerns.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">CONFLICT OF INTEREST</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Company respects your right to engage in lawful activities that are private in nature and
                                        do not conflict with or reflect unfavorably upon Company. You are responsible for
                                        avoiding situations that could lead to a conflict of interest and for avoiding undue outside
                                        influence upon decisions or actions required in performance of your work. This includes
                                        but is not limited to, the acceptance of gifts, bonuses, loans, entertainment, hospitality or
                                        anything else involving personal gain from those who conduct business with Company.
                                        This also includes using one's position or the knowledge gained in one's position with
                                        Company for personal gain or advantage for oneself or for a third party. In any event, an
                                        employee is required to report to Human Resources.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Should there be any doubt in your mind, you should discuss the matter with your
                                        manager and/or Human Resources and obtain a written approval from Company to
                                        participate in the questioned activity. Failure to notify Company in writing and receive
                                        written approval may result in disciplinary action up to and including termination of
                                        employment.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        All employees are under a continuing obligation to make full disclosure to their manager
                                        of all situations involving either actual or potential conflicts of interest, immediately and
                                        whenever such situations arise. An employee may be discharged for having engaged in
                                        conduct, which constitutes a conflict, or for failing to promptly disclose a situation
                                        involving an actual or potential conflict of interest.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">OUTSIDE EMPLOYMENT POLICY</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Outside business activities and employment are discouraged for full-time employees.
                                        However, you may engage in outside employment during the time other than regular
                                        working hours, provided that such employment does not, in any way, use your position or
                                        relationship at Company or affect your work. This includes any work relationship such
                                        as employment, consulting, accepting payment from any company that does business
                                        with or is a competitor of Company or engaging in any financial, business or other
                                        relationships with present or potential suppliers, contractors, agents, competitors or
                                        customers of Company.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">NO DATING POLICY</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Company asks that you discuss any prospective outside employment with your manager
                                        to ensure that there will not be any conflict. Submit the details in writing and receive
                                        approval from Company. If your outside work may use your position or relationships at
                                        Company or affect your work, Company will disapprove your request. If you failed to
                                        get Company approval and are found in violation of this policy, you are subject to
                                        termination.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        In order to promote the efficient operation of the Company’s business, to facilitate the
                                        legitimate business concerns of company, and to avoid misunderstandings, complaints of
                                        favoritism, other problems of supervision, security, and morale, and possible claims of
                                        sexual harassment, all employees are forbidden to date or pursue romantic and/or sexual
                                        relationships with employees whom they supervise, either directly or indirectly. If an
                                        issue develops in this regard you need to notify your immediate supervisor immediately.
                                        Employees who violate this guideline will be subject to discipline, up to and including
                                        termination of employment.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Company also discourages dating of co-workers. Company reserves the right, based on
                                        individual circumstances, to transfer one or both employees to avoid problems that may
                                        arise if co-workers are employed in the same department. If a dating relationship between
                                        co-workers becomes disruptive, or is the basis for employee complaints, Company will
                                        take appropriate corrective action, which may include requesting that one of the
                                        employees, at the choice of the two involved employees, resign their employment with
                                        Company. Company believes that this policy helps to avoid claims of favoritism, office
                                        disruption, and the potential for harassment complaints.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        No employee should feel pressured to date or otherwise become involved with another
                                        co-worker, customer, vendor, or supervisor. Please come to Human Resources if you
                                        experience any such pressure or problems.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">COMPLAINT AND PROBLEM PROCEDURE</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        One of the primary goals of Company is job satisfaction of all of its employees. Each of
                                        its personnel policies was formulated with this objective in mind. Nonetheless, Company
                                        recognizes that problems can and do arise in any operation.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Employees who have a job-related issue, question, or complaint should first discuss it
                                        with their immediate manager. If the issue cannot be resolved at this level, Company
                                        encourages employees to contact Human Resources.
                                        All complaints must be presented within ten (10) working days of the date when you
                                        knew the grounds for it. There is no time limitation on the presentation of problems.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Any reported allegations of harassment, discrimination or retaliation will be investigated
                                        promptly. The investigation may include individual interviews with the parties involved
                                        and, where necessary, with individuals who may have observed the alleged conduct or
                                        may have other relevant knowledge.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Confidentiality will be maintained throughout the investigatory process to the extent
                                        consistent with adequate investigation and appropriate corrective action.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Retaliation against an individual for reporting harassment or discrimination or for
                                        participating in an investigation of a claim of harassment or discrimination is a serious
                                        violation of this policy and, like harassment or discrimination itself, will be subject to
                                        disciplinary action. Acts of retaliation should be reported immediately and will be
                                        promptly investigated and addressed. Misconduct constituting harassment, discrimination
                                        or retaliation will be dealt with appropriately.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">CORRECTIVE PROCEDURE</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Company believes in allowing their employees to correct any behavior that may be
                                        deemed inappropriate per Company policies. When that behavior does not lead to
                                        immediate dismissal Company will employ a progressive disciplinary system.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        That system will be as follows:
                                    </p>
                                    <ol>
                                        <li>Offense - Verbal Warning & Documented in a written format</li>
                                        <li>Offense - Written Warning</li>
                                        <li>Offense - Discipline up to termination</li>
                                    </ol>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">CRISIS SUSPENSION</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        An employee who commits any serious violation of Company policies at minimum will
                                        be suspended without pay pending an investigation of the situation. Following the
                                        investigation, the employee may be terminated without any previous disciplinary action
                                        having been taken.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">DRUG-FREE WORKPLACE POLICY</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        <b>Purpose:</b> Company is committed to a drug free workplace. It is the intention of
                                        Company to provide a drug free work environment through establishment of policies for
                                        the control of illegal drug use and use of cannabis products by its employees.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Accordingly, by this policy, Company intends to establish guidelines against alcohol and
                                        substance abuse that may negatively affect an employee’s performance or may place at
                                        risk any other employee or Company.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        <b>Policy:</b> To protect our employees, customers and Company against the adverse effects
                                        that may result from employee involvement with illegal drugs, controlled substances,
                                        cannabis products, or alcohol on the premises, Company will take any action that is
                                        morally and legally acceptable to prevent the possession, sale, transfer or use of illegal
                                        drugs, controlled substances, or alcohol in the workplace. Company will not tolerate any
                                        form of illegal drug use, controlled substances including cannabis products, or alcohol
                                        use that violates this policy.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        All new employees and rehired employees are required, as a condition of employment, to
                                        be free of controlled Substances in their body.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        The use of prescription drugs may produce effects that may interfere with job
                                        performance or pose safety risks to co-workers. Therefore, any employee who is taking
                                        prescription medications must contact Management for policy requirements.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        When an employee is involved in an on-the-job accident, Company reserves the right to
                                        require the employee or employees involved to submit to drug, controlled substances, or
                                        alcohol testing.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Company endorses a zero-tolerance policy. When alcohol, controlled substances, or drug
                                        abuse interferes with the employee’s ability to perform his or her job in satisfactory and
                                        safe manner, the employee may be discharged.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Company’s policy of low tolerance for illegal drug, controlled substances, or alcohol use
                                        is designed to ensure a safe, drug-free workplace for all employees.
                                        Under this policy and Company’s Drug Free Program, conduct set out as follows shall be
                                        grounds for corrective action, up to and including termination:
                                    </p>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        An employee who tests positive for illegal drugs shall be terminated pursuant to
                                        this policy.
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Refusal to submit to physical examinations, including, but not limited to,
                                        screening tests for illegal drugs or controlled substances which Company may,
                                        from time to time, require pursuant to this program shall be terminated.
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Unauthorized use or possession of, or trafficking in illegal drugs, controlled
                                        substances, or alcohol at work, in Company vehicles or on Company or customer
                                        property, or reporting for work or being at work under the influence of illegal
                                        drugs, controlled substances, or alcohol.
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Refusal to comply with published Company security policies, including but not
                                        limited to, reasonable searches of person and/or personal property for illegal
                                        drugs, controlled substances, alcohol, or other contraband.
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Any off-work misconduct which reflects negatively on an employee’s suitability
                                        for continued employment with Company, and/or causes or has the potential to
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        Company prohibits all employees from manufacturing, distributing, dispensing,
                                        possessing or using an illegal drug in or on Company’s premises or while
                                        conducting Company business. Employees are also prohibited from misusing
                                        legally prescribed or over the counter (OTC) drugs. Law enforcement personnel
                                        shall be notified, as appropriate, when criminal activity is suspected.
                                    </MudText>

                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">WORKPLACE INSPECTIONS</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Company wishes to maintain a work environment that is free of illegal drugs, alcohol,
                                        controlled substances such as cannabis products, firearms, explosives, stolen property, or
                                        other improper materials. We require the cooperation of all employees in administering
                                        this policy. Company, by any agent or representative at any time, either with or without
                                        prior notice, may make personal and property inspections, including in your absence.
                                        Such inspections may include e-mail, computer files and other records of computer use.
                                        Accordingly, please be aware that you do not have an expectation of privacy in
                                        Company-provided e-mail or internet access, Company-owned computers, other
                                        Company property, or your own property or person when on Company premises.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        To protect the property and to ensure the safety of Company employees and others,
                                        Company reserves the right to conduct searches, consistent with the law. Employees who
                                        wish to avoid any inspection of their property should not bring it to work.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">ABSENCES</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        All employees are expected to work on a regular, consistent basis and complete their
                                        regularly scheduled hours per week. Excessive absenteeism may result in disciplinary
                                        action, up to and including termination. Disciplinary action taken because of absenteeism
                                        will be considered on an individual basis, following a review of the employee’s absentee
                                        and overall work record.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        If you know you will be absent in advance, please inform your manager. If this is not
                                        possible, you must telephone your manager and/or Human Resources at least one (1) hour
                                        prior to the beginning of your work schedule.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Unreported absences (No call/No show) will result in immediate discipline. Discipline for
                                        No call/ No show during a calendar 12-month period will be as follows:
                                    </p>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <b><u>First Offense</u></b> - 3 day suspension
                                    </MudText>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <b><u>Second Offense</u></b> - Termination
                                    </MudText>
                                    <br />
                                    <p>
                                        Any employee who does not call or report to work for three (3) consecutive days will be
                                        considered to have voluntarily resigned employment at Company.
                                        Prior to taking a leave of absence for purposes of vacation, personal leave, military or
                                        jury duty, or other planned absence, an Employee Leave Request Form, available from
                                        your manager, or line request, should be submitted to and final approved by the
                                        department head manager.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Employee Leave Requests should be submitted at least two weeks prior to the scheduled
                                        leave date, unless the request is due to an unexpected emergency. The nature of the
                                        emergency should then be shared with the manager.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        To return to work from an accident or medical leave, all employees must present a
                                        doctor’s release.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Any employee who fails to return to work at the expiration of a personal leave of absence
                                        will be deemed to have abandoned their job, unless Company is notified of a reason,
                                        satisfactory to management, for not returning to work at the end of the leave of absence.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">TARDINESS</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Employees must be prepared to start work promptly at the beginning of their shift. Your
                                        scheduled time is the time that you are expected to be on your job, not the time that you
                                        arrive to work. Repeated tardiness is grounds for termination. If it is not possible for you
                                        to begin work at your scheduled time, please speak with the Manager on duty.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">EMPLOYMENT TERMINATION/RESIGNATION/LAYOFF</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <b><u>Termination</u></b> - Company will not tolerate any action by an employee that may
                                        have a detrimental effect on the business activities, property, staff, or customers
                                        of Company, or that interferes with the rights of, its employees, or customers.
                                        Any such actions will result in employee disciplinary action up to and including
                                        termination without advance notice. However, your employment may also be
                                        terminated for poor performance, misconduct, excessive absences, tardiness, or
                                        other violations of the Company rules, as elsewhere described
                                    </MudText>
                                    <br />
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <b><u>Resignation</u></b> - If you plan to leave Company, as a courtesy to us, you are asked to
                                        give Company at least two (2) weeks written notice so that we will have the
                                        opportunity to recruit a replacement prior to your leaving. Please note, however,
                                        that you are an at-will employee and may leave Company at any time, without
                                        any notice. In your letter of resignation, should you elect to provide one, please
                                        specify the last day you will be at work and include the reason for leaving, e.g.,
                                        going back to school, moving out of state, starting own business, found another
                                        job, etc. Failure to provide the requested notice will make you ineligible for
                                        rehire.
                                    </MudText>
                                    <br />
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <b><u>Layoff</u></b> - Generally occurs due to business necessity and is initiated by Company.
                                        An example would occur if Company decided to reduce the number of employees
                                        during an economic downturn or during a time when there was a significant
                                        reduction of work. Generally speaking, Company would normally be hopeful that
                                        the circumstances that necessitated the reduction in personnel would turn around
                                        and allow the laid off employees to be recalled.
                                    </MudText>
                                    <br />
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <b><u>Separation</u></b> - Is an involuntary termination that is generally necessitated by
                                        circumstances beyond the Company's control. A separation could occur if there
                                        were a doctor that informed Company an employee was not medically able to
                                        work, or it was found an employee was not capable of performing the work to
                                        which assigned.
                                    </MudText>
                                    <br />
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <b><u>Final Paycheck</u></b> - Employees will receive their final paycheck within the time
                                        required by law. The final paycheck for employees who resign with at least
                                        seventy-two (72) hours advance notice will be provided on the last day worked.
                                        Final paychecks will be issued within seventy-two (72) hours of resignation to
                                        employees who resign without providing at least seventy-two (72) hours advance
                                        notice. Employees who are terminated involuntarily will be provided their final
                                        paycheck on the last day worked. You are requested to give a two-week notice of
                                        your plans to leave Company. A notice is important so that we have time to hire
                                        someone to take your place. Giving a two-week notice is a professional courtesy
                                        and assures that you are eligible for re-hire and will not have a “left without
                                        resignation notice” on your employment record.
                                    </MudText>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">EXIT INTERVIEW</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Whether a voluntary resignation or termination, Company management would like to
                                        conduct an exit interview to discuss the employee’s reasons for leaving and any other
                                        impressions that the employee may have about Company. This exit interview will be
                                        conducted by your immediate Human Resources Manager or the President.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">RETURN OF COMPANY PROPERTY</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Any Company property issued to employees must be returned to Company at the time of
                                        termination. Employees will be responsible for any lost or damaged items. Any property
                                        which has been assigned to an employee must be returned prior to receiving their final
                                        paycheck. If an employee fails to return any Company property assigned to them, the
                                        cost of that property will be deducted from their final paycheck.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>

                    </ChildContent>
                </MudExpansionPanel>

                @*********Leaves Of Absence Section*********@
                <MudExpansionPanel>
                    <TitleContent>
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.h5">LEAVES OF ABSENCE</MudText>
                    </TitleContent>
                    <ChildContent>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">PAID VACATION</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>

                                        <b>Eligibility:</b> Company provides Paid Vacation benefits to full-time employees. Full-time
                                        employees who work for 30 days or more in a year are eligible for vacation benefits only
                                        after Probationary Period is successfully completed.<i>
                                            “Anniversary year” means the 12
                                            months period immediately following the date of hire and each anniversary date of hire
                                            thereafter.
                                        </i>
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Upon successful completion of Probationary Period, a new hired permanent full-time
                                        employee will be entitled to use Paid Vacation time based on his/her years of service with
                                        Company as follows:
                                    </p>

                                    <MudTable Items="@vacationPlans">
                                        <HeaderContent>
                                            <MudTh>
                                                Anniversary Years of
                                                Continuous Service
                                            </MudTh>
                                            <MudTh>
                                                Maximum Vacation Earned
                                                in 12-Month Period
                                            </MudTh>
                                        </HeaderContent>
                                        <RowTemplate>
                                            <MudTd DataLabel="Years">@context.Year</MudTd>
                                                <MudTd DataLabel="vacation">@context.Vacation</MudTd>
                                            </RowTemplate>
                                        </MudTable>
                                        <br />
                                        <p>
                                            Employees will accrue 5 Paid Vacation days upon successful completion of Probationary
                                            Period. Employees will only be allowed to accrue up to 15 days. A cap will be placed on
                                            Paid Vacation time accrual and once such cap is reached and Paid Vacation time are
                                            earned, but not taken, no further Paid Vacation time or vacation pay will accrue until the
                                            balance of Paid Vacation time falls below the cap.
                                        </p>
                                        <p>
                                            If a regular full-time employee works less than one hundred percent (100%) of his/her
                                            hours in a given week, the rate of accrual will be prorated based on the percentage of time
                                            worked.
                                        </p>
                                        <p>
                                            Paid Vacation time accruals will not be earned during unpaid leaves of absence,
                                            regardless of reason, including, but not limited to, medical leave (inclusive of employees
                                            paid by disability or workers’ compensation benefits), pregnancy-related medical leave,
                                            Family and Medical Leave Act, California Family Rights Act, military leave and personal
                                            leave.
                                        </p>
                                        <p>
                                            <b>How to Request Paid Vacation Time:</b> Any employee planning to take a vacation should
                                            notify and seek approval from his/her manager at least two (2) weeks in advance of the
                                            planned Paid Vacation commencement date. Management reserves the right to schedule
                                            and approve Paid Vacation requests.
                                        </p>
                                        <p>
                                            <b>Accrued Vacation Paid on Separation:</b> If an employee resigns or is terminated without
                                            having taken accrued Paid Vacation time, he/she will be paid for all accrued, unused
                                            vacation time. Any unused Paid Vacation time will be prorated on a monthly basis and
                                            paid out at the final rate of pay in effect at the time of the separation.
                                        </p>
                                    </MudText>
                                </ChildContent>
