                            <MudExpansionPanel>
                                <TitleContent>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">PREGNANCY-RELATED DISABILITY LEAVES</MudText>
                                </TitleContent>
                                <ChildContent>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                        <p>
                                            Company will provide unpaid leave for employees who need to be absent from work for
                                            pregnancy-related disabilities in accordance with the California Fair Employment and
                                            Housing Act ("FEHA").
                                        </p>
                                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                            <b><u>Eligibility:</u></b> <br />
                                            This leave is available to all full- and part-time California employees who are
                                            medically disabled due to pregnancy, childbirth, or a related medical condition.
                                        </MudText>
                                        <br />
                                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                            <b><u>Duration:</u></b> <br />
                                            The maximum pregnancy-related disability leave available is four (4) months in
                                            connection with any one pregnancy. In accordance with California law, the
                                            employee may be separately entitled to leave under the CFRA after her child is
                                            born.
                                        </MudText>
                                        <br />
                                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                            <b><u>Use of Paid Leave:</u></b> <br />
                                            Leaves for pregnancy-related disabilities are generally unpaid.<br />
                                            Employees may wish to apply for any state disability insurance (SDI) or Paid
                                            Family Leave (PFL) benefits that may be available.<br />
                                            Once all available paid leave has been exhausted, the leave will be unpaid by
                                            Company.<br />
                                        </MudText> <br />
                                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                            <b><u>Requesting Pregnancy-Related Disability Leave:</u></b> <br />
                                            Requests for leave should be made to Manager/President. Before the leave is
                                            approved, the employee may be required to provide medical certification of the
                                            pregnancy-related disability giving rise to a request for a leave of absence. The
                                            employee may also be required to provide periodic updates of her status, such as
                                            the expected date of return and intent to return to work.
                                        </MudText> <br />
                                        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                            <b><u>Reinstatement:</u></b><br />
                                            If the employee has not exceeded the maximum leave of absence available under
                                            this policy, she will be entitled to reinstatement in accordance with the provisions
                                            of the FEHA. If the former position no longer exists due to business reasons
                                            unrelated to the leave, or if preserving the employee’s former position would
                                            substantially undermine the Company’s ability to operate safely and efficiently,
                                            the employee will be assigned to a comparable position, if one is available. If the
                                            pregnancy disability leave exceeds the maximum allowed by this policy,
                                            employment will cease. However, once the employee is able to return to work,
                                            she may apply for any open positions for which she qualifies.
                                        </MudText> <br />
                                        <p>
                                            It is the employee’s responsibility to report to work at the end of the approved
                                            leave. If the employee accepts other employment or fails to return to work
                                            following the expiration of the leave, Company will consider the employee to
                                            have resigned.
                                        </p>
                                    </MudText>
                                </ChildContent>
